      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait what does the goblin thing have to do with physics tho?? i wasnt asking for a story or anything, can u just explain the actual scientific mechanism without the metaphors please?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. To explain the scientific mechanism of entanglement, imagine two particles as two separate, independent systems. In classical physics, if you measure the state of one particle, it will be determined, and the state of the other particle will be independent of it. However, in quantum mechanics, entanglement introduces a non-local connection between the particles, where the state of one particle is correlated with the state of the other, even if they are separated by large distances.\n\nWhen a measurement is made on one particle, it instantly affects the state of the other entangled particle, regardless of the distance between them. This effect happens even if they are separated by billions of kilometers, which seems to contradict the fundamental laws of space and time. The exact mechanism behind entanglement is still not fully understood, but it's a fundamental aspect of quantum mechanics that has been experimentally confirmed many times.",
      "source": "target",
