    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok i get the correlation part, but you mentioned earlier that it's \"spooky\" or unlike anything in classical physics. why is it described that way? like, what is it about the connection that feels so \"unexplained\" compared to just regular physics?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"spooky\" aspect of entanglement comes from the fact that it seems to imply a non-local, instantaneous connection between particles, which challenges our classical understanding of space and time. In classical physics, information can't travel faster than the speed of light, so if two particles are separated by a large distance, measuring one particle shouldn't instantaneously affect the other.\n\nHowever, entanglement seems to allow for this instantaneous effect, which is difficult to reconcile with our everyday experience of the world. It's like the connection between the two particles is \"tuned into\" a frequency that allows them to communicate with each other instantaneously, regardless of the distance between them.\n\nThis aspect of entanglement is often referred to as \"non-locality\" or \"spooky action at a distance,\" coined by Albert Einstein, who famously said, \"God does not play dice with the universe,\" implying that the randomness and unpredictability of quantum mechanics is somehow unnatural or \"spooky.\" The connection between entanglement and non-locality is still an active area of research and debate in the physics community.",
      "source": "target",
